{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775849144559,"sessionID":"ses_287256e9fffeSRz9kwMdlXsQmu","part":{"id":"prt_d78db776f001LwKU6S33deG9Xc","messageID":"msg_d78db6b8000115zoxnMSBVusjm","sessionID":"ses_287256e9fffeSRz9kwMdlXsQmu","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_96b7589663f34cb387e21001","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-009/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-009/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-009: Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: This proposal defines the HTTP reverse proxy core implementation for the `pkg/router` module in the AgentCube project. The router is responsible for:\n6: \n7: 1. **Session-aware traffic routing** - Resolve or create sessions via workload manager, route HTTP requests to appropriate sandbox endpoints\n8: 2. **Reverse proxy functionality** - Proxy HTTP traffic to sandbox pods with proper URL rewriting and header forwarding\n9: 3. **JWT authentication** - Sign outbound requests to sandboxes with JWT tokens for authentication\n10: 4. **Connection management** - Handle connection pooling, health checks, and concurrency limiting\n11: 5. **Activity tracking** - Update session last-activity timestamps in the store for idle cleanup\n12: \n13: The router serves as the primary entry point for all HTTP invocations targeting agent runtimes and code interpreters.\n14: \n15: ## Scope\n16: \n17: **Module:** `pkg/router`  \n18: **Language:** Go  \n19: **Size:** M\n20: \n21: ### In Scope\n22: \n23: 1. **Session Manager** (`pkg/router/session/manager.go`)\n24:    - `SessionManager` interface and implementation\n25:    - Session resolution from `x-agentcube-session-id` header\n26:    - Workload manager integration for session creation\n27:    - `SandboxInfo` caching and lookup\n28: \n29: 2. **Reverse Proxy Core** (`pkg/router/proxy/proxy.go`)\n30:    - `httputil.NewSingleHostReverseProxy` wrapper\n31:    - Custom `Director` for URL rewriting and header injection\n32:    - JWT generation and injection for sandbox authentication\n33:    - Error handling and response mapping\n34: \n35: 3. **Routing Rules Engine** (`pkg/router/routing/rules.go`)\n36:    - Entry point selection by path matching\n37:    - Protocol normalization (http/https)\n38:    - URL scheme detection and prefixing\n39: \n40: 4. **Connection Pooling** (`pkg/router/pool/pool.go`)\n41:    - Shared `http.Transport` configuration\n42:    - Connection reuse settings\n43:    - Idle connection management\n44: \n45: 5. **Health Check System** (`pkg/router/health/checker.go`)\n46:    - Liveness endpoint (`/health/live`)\n47:    - Readiness endpoint (`/health/ready`)\n48:    - Dependency health verification\n49: \n50: 6. **HTTP Server** (`pkg/router/server.go`)\n51:    - Gin router setup with middleware stack\n52:    - HTTP/2 and h2c support\n53:    - TLS configuration\n54:    - Graceful shutdown\n55: \n56: 7. **Middleware Components**\n57:    - Concurrency limiting semaphore (`pkg/router/middleware/semaphore.go`)\n58:    - Gin logger and recovery\n59:    - Forwarding headers injection (`X-Forwarded-Host`, `X-Forwarded-Proto`, `X-Forwarded-For`)\n60: \n61: 8. **JWT Manager** (`pkg/router/auth/jwt.go`)\n62:    - RS256 JWT signing\n63:    - Key generation and storage (`picod-router-identity` secret)\n64:    - `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret` bootstrap logic\n65: \n66: 9. **Invocation Handlers** (`pkg/router/handler/invocation.go`)\n67:    - AgentRuntime invocation endpoint\n68:    - CodeInterpreter invocation endpoint\n69:    - Session resolution and activity tracking\n70: \n71: ### Out of Scope\n72: \n73: - Workload Manager reconciler logic (separate controller component)\n74: - Session store implementation (uses existing `pkg/store` module)\n75: - CRD type definitions (defined in `pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1`)\n76: - Python SDK CLI commands (separate Python package)\n77: - PicoD daemon inside sandboxes (separate `picod` binary)\n78: - Agentd idle cleanup controller (separate controller component)\n79: - Volcano scheduler integration (optional, separate component)\n80: \n81: ## Impact Analysis\n82: \n83: ### Dependencies\n84: \n85: | Dependency | Type | Reason |\n86: |------------|------|--------|\n87: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/client-go` | Required | Generated Kubernetes client for Secret operations |\n88: | `k8s.io/client-go` | Required | In-cluster config, Secret API |\n89: | `k8s.io/api/core/v1` | Required | Secret, ServiceAccount types |\n90: | `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/api/errors` | Required | Kubernetes error handling |\n91: | `github.com/gin-gonic/gin` | Required | HTTP framework |\n92: | `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` | Required | JWT signing (RS256) |\n93: | `github.com/redis/go-redis/v9` | Required | Session store client |\n94: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/store` | Required | Session store interface |\n95: | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/apis/runtime/v1alpha1` | Required | Type constants (kinds) |\n96: | `net/http/httputil` | Required | Reverse proxy |\n97: | `golang.org/x/net/http2` | Required | HTTP/2 support |\n98: \n99: ### Downstream Consumers\n100: \n101: 1. **External Clients** - HTTP API consumers invoking agent runtimes\n102: 2. **Python SDK** - Uses router endpoints for invocation\n103: 3. **CLI Tool** - Routes commands through router\n104: 4. **Agentd Controller** - Monitors session activity timestamps\n105: 5. **Workload Manager** - Receives session creation requests from router\n106: \n107: ### Breaking Changes\n108: \n109: None — this is the initial implementation of the router module.\n110: \n111: ### Migration Path\n112: \n113: Not applicable for initial implementation. Future migrations may include:\n114: - JWT algorithm migration (RS256 → ES256)\n115: - Session ID format changes (UUID → nanoid)\n116: - Protocol versioning (HTTP/1.1 → HTTP/2 mandatory)\n117: \n118: ## Alternatives Considered\n119: \n120: ### Alternative 1: Use Envoy as Data Plane\n121: \n122: **Approach:** Deploy Envoy sidecar or standalone proxy, configure via xDS API.\n123: \n124: **Pros:**\n125: - Industry-standard proxy with extensive features\n126: - Built-in observability (metrics, tracing)\n127: - Advanced load balancing algorithms\n128: - Automatic retries and circuit breaking\n129: \n130: **Cons:**\n131: - Significant operational complexity\n132: - Requires xDS control plane implementation\n133: - Over-engineering for single-tenant routing\n134: - Steeper learning curve for debugging\n135: - Additional resource overhead\n136: \n137: **Decision:** Rejected. Envoy is overkill for AgentCube's use case; Go's built-in `httputil.ReverseProxy` provides sufficient functionality with simpler operations.\n138: \n139: ### Alternative 2: Use Traefik or Kong API Gateway\n140: \n141: **Approach:** Deploy off-the-shelf API gateway, configure via CRDs or admin API.\n142: \n143: **Pros:**\n144: - Rich feature set out of the box\n145: - Managed authentication/authorization\n146: - Plugin ecosystem\n147: - Dashboard and observability\n148: \n149: **Cons:**\n150: - Less control over session logic\n151: - Custom middleware development still required\n152: - Additional deployment complexity\n153: - Licensing considerations (Kong)\n154: - Tight coupling to external project\n155: \n156: **Decision:** Rejected. Custom implementation provides full control over session-aware routing logic and aligns with AgentCube's Kubernetes-native architecture.\n157: \n158: ### Alternative 3: Direct Client-to-Sandbox Routing\n159: \n160: **Approach:** Clients discover sandbox IPs directly from Kubernetes API, bypass router.\n161: \n162: **Pros:**\n163: - Eliminates proxy hop (lower latency)\n164: - Simpler architecture (one less component)\n165: - No single point of failure\n166: \n167: **Cons:**\n168: - Exposes internal pod IPs to clients\n169: - No centralized session management\n170: - Clients must handle Kubernetes API complexity\n171: - No JWT injection for sandbox authentication\n172: - Harder to implement idle cleanup\n173: - Security concerns (direct pod access)\n174: \n175: **Decision:** Rejected. Router provides essential abstraction layer for session management, security, and lifecycle tracking.\n176: \n177: ### Alternative 4: Use Kubernetes Service Mesh (Istio/Linkerd)\n178: \n179: **Approach:** Leverage service mesh for traffic routing and authentication.\n180: \n181: **Pros:**\n182: - mTLS between services\n183: - Advanced traffic management\n184: - Observability built-in\n185: - Policy enforcement\n186: \n187: **Cons:**\n188: - Massive operational overhead\n189: - Requires mesh installation on all clusters\n190: - Complex configuration (VirtualServices, DestinationRules)\n191: - Over-engineering for simple proxy use case\n192: - Performance overhead from sidecars\n193: \n194: **Decision:** Rejected. Service mesh is unnecessary complexity; router is a single, focused component with minimal dependencies.\n195: \n196: ### Alternative 5: WebSocket-Only Proxy\n197: \n198: **Approach:** Use WebSocket connections for all sandbox communication instead of HTTP proxy.\n199: \n200: **Pros:**\n201: - Persistent connections (lower latency for repeated calls)\n202: - Full-duplex communication\n203: - Better for streaming use cases\n204: \n205: **Cons:**\n206: - Breaking change for HTTP clients\n207: - More complex connection management\n208: - Harder to debug (non-standard tooling)\n209: - Load balancers may not support WebSocket well\n210: - Session state tied to connection lifetime\n211: \n212: **Decision:** Rejected. HTTP proxy is more compatible with existing tools and client libraries; WebSocket can be added as future enhancement.\n213: \n214: ## Implementation Plan\n215: \n216: ### Phase 1: Foundation (Week 1)\n217: \n218: 1. **Scaffold Directory Structure**\n219:    ```\n220:    pkg/router/\n221:    ├── server.go              # HTTP server setup\n222:    ├── session/\n223:    │   ├── manager.go         # SessionManager interface\n224:    │   ├── sandbox_info.go    # SandboxInfo type\n225:    │   └── errors.go          # Session-related errors\n226:    ├── proxy/\n227:    │   ├── proxy.go           # ReverseProxy wrapper\n228:    │   ├── director.go        # Request director\n229:    │   └── transport.go       # HTTP transport config\n230:    ├── routing/\n231:    │   ├── rules.go           # Routing rules engine\n232:    │   └── entry_point.go     # Entry point selection\n233:    ├── auth/\n234:    │   ├── jwt.go             # JWTManager, signing\n235:    │   └── keys.go            # Key generation/storage\n236:    ├── middleware/\n237:    │   ├── semaphore.go       # Concurrency limiter\n238:    │   ├── headers.go         # Forwarding headers\n239:    │   └── logger.go          # Request logging\n240:    ├── health/\n241:    │   └── checker.go         # Health endpoints\n242:    ├── pool/\n243:    │   └── pool.go            # Connection pooling\n244:    └── handler/\n245:        └── invocation.go      # Invocation handlers\n246:    ```\n247: \n248: 2. **Define Core Interfaces**\n249:    - `SessionManager` interface\n250:    - `Proxy` interface\n251:    - `JWTManager` interface\n252: \n253: 3. **Implement Session Manager**\n254:    - Load session from store by ID\n255:    - Create session via workload manager POST\n256:    - Cache `SandboxInfo` in memory\n257: \n258: ### Phase 2: Proxy Core (Week 2)\n259: \n260: 4. **Implement ReverseProxy Wrapper**\n261:    - Wrap `httputil.NewSingleHostReverseProxy`\n262:    - Custom `Director` function\n263:    - Error handler for connection failures\n264: \n265: 5. **Implement JWT Manager**\n266:    - Generate RS256 key pair\n267:    - Store/load from Kubernetes Secret\n268:    - Sign JWT with sandbox claims\n269: \n270: 6. **Implement Routing Rules**\n271:    - Path-based entry point matching\n272:    - Protocol normalization\n273:    - URL scheme detection\n274: \n275: ### Phase 3: HTTP Server (Week 3)\n276: \n277: 7. **Implement HTTP Server**\n278:    - Gin router setup\n279:    - HTTP/2 and h2c configuration\n280:    - TLS support (optional)\n281:    - Graceful shutdown\n282: \n283: 8. **Add Middleware Stack**\n284:    - Concurrency semaphore\n285:    - Gin logger and recovery\n286:    - Forwarding headers injection\n287: \n288: 9. **Implement Health Endpoints**\n289:    - `/health/live` - always returns 200\n290:    - `/health/ready` - checks session manager availability\n291: \n292: ### Phase 4: Integration (Week 4)\n293: \n294: 10. **Implement Invocation Handlers**\n295:     - AgentRuntime invocation (`POST /v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path`)\n296:     - CodeInterpreter invocation (`POST /v1/namespaces/:namespace/code-interpreters/:name/invocations/*path`)\n297:     - Session resolution and activity tracking\n298: \n299: 11. **Write Unit Tests**\n300:     - Session manager tests with mock store\n301:     - Proxy tests with test HTTP server\n302:     - JWT tests with key generation\n303:     - Routing rule tests\n304: \n305: 12. **Write Integration Tests**\n306:     - End-to-end invocation flow\n307:     - Session creation and reuse\n308:     - Error handling scenarios\n309:     - Concurrency limit enforcement\n310: \n311: ## Router Architecture\n312: \n313: ### Request Flow\n314: \n315: ```\n316: Client Request\n317:     ↓\n318: [1] Extract x-agentcube-session-id header\n319:     ↓\n320: [2] Session Manager: Load or Create\n321:     ├── If header empty → POST to WorkloadManager\n322:     └── If header present → Load from Store\n323:     ↓\n324: [3] Get SandboxInfo with EntryPoints\n325:     ↓\n326: [4] Select Entry Point by path matching\n327:     ↓\n328: [5] Build upstream URL (protocol + endpoint)\n329:     ↓\n330: [6] Generate JWT (RS256) for sandbox authentication\n331:     ↓\n332: [7] ReverseProxy with custom Director\n333:     ├── Set Host, Path\n334:     ├── Inject Authorization: Bearer <JWT>\n335:     ├── Set X-Forwarded-* headers\n336:     └── Apply concurrency semaphore\n337:     ↓\n338: [8] Update LastActivity timestamp in Store\n339:     ↓\n340: Sandbox Pod (with PicoD daemon)\n341: ```\n342: \n343: ### Concurrency Model\n344: \n345: ```\n346: ┌───────────────────────────────────────┐\n347: │         Semaphore (capacity: 1000)    │\n348: └───────────────────────────────────────┘\n349:                     ↓\n350:     ┌───────────────┼───────────────┐\n351:     ↓               ↓               ↓\n352: [Request 1]   [Request 2]   [Request N]\n353:     ↓               ↓               ↓\n354: [Session Res] [Session Res] [Session Res]\n355:     ↓               ↓               ↓\n356: [JWT Gen]     [JWT Gen]     [JWT Gen]\n357:     ↓               ↓               ↓\n358: [ReverseProxy] [ReverseProxy] [ReverseProxy]\n359:     ↓               ↓               ↓\n360: [Sandbox 1]    [Sandbox 2]    [Sandbox N]\n361: ```\n362: \n363: ### Error Handling Matrix\n364: \n365: | Error Type | HTTP Status | Response Body |\n366: |------------|-------------|---------------|\n367: | Session not found | 404 | `{\"error\":\"session not found\",\"sessionId\":\"...\"}` |\n368: | Sandbox template not found | 404 | `{\"error\":\"sandbox template not found\",\"namespace\":\"...\",\"name\":\"...\"}` |\n369: | No entry points | 404 | `{\"error\":\"no entry point found for sandbox\"}` |\n370: | JWT signing failure | 500 | `{\"error\":\"failed to sign request\",\"code\":\"JWT_SIGNING_FAILED\"}` |\n371: | Connection refused | 502 | `{\"error\":\"sandbox unreachable\"}` |\n372: | Connection timeout | 504 | `{\"error\":\"sandbox timeout\"}` |\n373: | Other proxy error | 502 | `{\"error\":\"sandbox unreachable\"}` |\n374: | Concurrency limit exceeded | 429 | `{\"error\":\"server overloaded, please try again later\",\"code\":\"SERVER_OVERLOADED\"}` |\n375: | Session manager not ready | 503 | `{\"error\":\"session manager not available\",\"status\":\"not ready\"}` |\n376: \n377: ## API Endpoints\n378: \n379: ### Invocation Endpoints\n380: \n381: | Method | Path | Description |\n382: |--------|------|-------------|\n383: | `POST` | `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path` | Invoke AgentRuntime sandbox |\n384: | `GET` | `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/agent-runtimes/:name/invocations/*path` | Invoke AgentRuntime sandbox (GET) |\n385: | `POST` | `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/code-interpreters/:name/invocations/*path` | Invoke CodeInterpreter sandbox |\n386: | `GET` | `/v1/namespaces/:namespace/code-interpreters/:name/invocations/*path` | Invoke CodeInterpreter sandbox (GET) |\n387: \n388: ### Health Endpoints\n389: \n390: | Method | Path | Description |\n391: |--------|------|-------------|\n392: | `GET` | `/health/live` | Liveness probe |\n393: | `GET` | `/health/ready` | Readiness probe |\n394: \n395: ### Request/Response Examples\n396: \n397: **Create Session (via WorkloadManager):**\n398: ```http\n399: POST /v1/namespaces/default/agent-runtimes/my-agent/invocations/chat HTTP/1.1\n400: Host: router.agentcube.local\n401: Content-Type: application/json\n402: \n403: {\"message\":\"hello\"}\n404: ```\n405: \n406: **Internal WorkloadManager Request:**\n407: ```http\n408: POST {WORKLOAD_MANAGER_URL}/v1/agent-runtime HTTP/1.1\n409: Content-Type: application/json\n410: Authorization: Bearer <service-account-token>\n411: \n412: {\n413:   \"kind\": \"AgentRuntime\",\n414:   \"name\": \"my-agent\",\n415:   \"namespace\": \"default\"\n416: }\n417: ```\n418: \n419: **WorkloadManager Response:**\n420: ```json\n421: {\n422:   \"sessionId\": \"sess-abc123\",\n423:   \"sandboxName\": \"my-agent-sandbox-x7y9z\",\n424:   \"entryPoints\": [\n425:     {\"protocol\":\"http\",\"endpoint\":\"10.244.1.5:8080\",\"path\":\"/chat\"}\n426:   ]\n427: }\n428: ```\n429: \n430: **Proxied Request to Sandbox:**\n431: ```http\n432: POST /chat HTTP/1.1\n433: Host: 10.244.1.5:8080\n434: Authorization: Bearer <jwt-signed-token>\n435: X-Forwarded-Host: router.agentcube.local\n436: X-Forwarded-Proto: http\n437: X-Forwarded-For: 192.168.1.100\n438: ```\n439: \n440: **Response:**\n441: ```http\n442: HTTP/1.1 200 OK\n443: x-agentcube-session-id: sess-abc123\n444: Content-Type: application/json\n445: \n446: {\"response\":\"hello back\"}\n447: ```\n448: \n449: ## Success Criteria\n450: \n451: - [ ] SessionManager resolves existing sessions from store\n452: - [ ] SessionManager creates new sessions via WorkloadManager when header missing\n453: - [ ] ReverseProxy correctly routes to sandbox endpoints\n454: - [ ] JWT injected for sandbox kinds (Sandbox, SandboxClaim)\n455: - [ ] Forwarding headers set correctly (X-Forwarded-Host, X-Forwarded-Proto, X-Forwarded-For)\n456: - [ ] Health endpoints respond correctly (live/ready)\n457: - [ ] Concurrency limiter enforces MaxConcurrentRequests\n458: - [ ] Connection pooling configured with shared Transport\n459: - [ ] Error mapping matches specification (404, 502, 504, 429, 503)\n460: - [ ] Session last-activity updated on successful invoke\n461: - [ ] HTTP/2 and h2c support working\n462: - [ ] TLS configuration optional but functional\n463: - [ ] Graceful shutdown within 10s\n464: - [ ] Unit test coverage >80%\n465: - [ ] Integration tests pass with test Kubernetes cluster\n466: \n467: ## Testing Strategy\n468: \n469: ### Unit Tests\n470: \n471: 1. **SessionManager Tests**\n472:    - `TestSessionManager_GetSandboxBySession_MissingHeader`\n473:    - `TestSessionManager_GetSandboxBySession_NotFound`\n474:    - `TestSessionManager_GetSandboxBySession_WorkloadManagerCreate`\n475:    - `TestSessionManager_GetSandboxBySession_WorkloadManagerError`\n476:    - `TestSessionManager_UpdateSessionLastActivity`\n477: \n478: 2. **ReverseProxy Tests**\n479:    - `TestProxy_Director_PathNormalization`\n480:    - `TestProxy_Director_HeaderInjection`\n481:    - `TestProxy_ErrorHandler_ConnectionRefused`\n482:    - `TestProxy_ErrorHandler_Timeout`\n483:    - `TestProxy_Transport_Reuse`\n484: \n485: 3. **JWTManager Tests**\n486:    - `TestJWTManager_GenerateToken`\n487:    - `TestJWTManager_VerifyToken`\n488:    - `TestJWTManager_TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret_Create`\n489:    - `TestJWTManager_TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret_Load`\n490: \n491: 4. **Routing Tests**\n492:    - `TestRoutingRules_SelectEntryPoint_MatchByPath`\n493:    - `TestRoutingRules_SelectEntryPoint_FirstEntry`\n494:    - `TestRoutingRules_NormalizeProtocol`\n495:    - `TestRoutingRules_DetectScheme`\n496: \n497: 5. **Middleware Tests**\n498:    - `TestSemaphoreMiddleware_LimitEnforcement`\n499:    - `TestSemaphoreMiddleware_Release`\n500:    - `TestHeadersMiddleware_XForwardedHeaders`\n501: \n502: 6. **Health Tests**\n503:    - `TestHealthChecker_Live`\n504:    - `TestHealthChecker_Ready_WithManager`\n505:    - `TestHealthChecker_Ready_WithoutManager`\n506: \n507: ### Integration Tests\n508: \n509: 1. **End-to-End Invocation Flow**\n510:    - Start test router server\n511:    - Mock WorkloadManager with test HTTP server\n512:    - Mock Redis store with test instance\n513:    - Create invocation request without session header\n514:    - Verify session creation and proxy to sandbox\n515: \n516: 2. **Session Reuse**\n517:    - Create session once\n518:    - Send multiple requests with session header\n519:    - Verify no additional WorkloadManager calls\n520:    - Verify LastActivity updates\n521: \n522: 3. **Error Scenarios**\n523:    - WorkloadManager returns 404\n524:    - Sandbox pod not reachable\n525:    - JWT signing failure\n526:    - Concurrency limit exceeded\n527: \n528: 4. **Concurrency Test**\n529:    - Send N concurrent requests (N > limit)\n530:    - Verify some requests get 429\n531:    - Verify successful requests complete\n532: \n533: ## Risks and Mitigations\n534: \n535: | Risk | Impact | Likelihood | Mitigation |\n536: |------|--------|------------|------------|\n537: | WorkloadManager unavailable | High | Medium | Cache sessions; return cached SandboxInfo if manager down; add circuit breaker |\n538: | Redis store unavailable | High | Low | In-memory fallback for session cache; log warnings; degrade gracefully |\n539: | JWT key secret creation fails | High | Low | Fail server startup; clear error message; manual secret creation fallback |\n540: | Connection exhaustion | Medium | Medium | Configure Transport.MaxIdleConns, MaxIdleConnsPerHost; monitor connection metrics |\n541: | Memory leak from session cache | Medium | Medium | Implement LRU eviction; TTL-based cleanup; integrate with agentd |\n542: | HTTP/2 h2c compatibility | Low | Medium | Test with major HTTP clients; fallback to HTTP/1.1 if negotiation fails |\n543: | Race condition in LastActivity | Low | Medium | Use atomic operations or mutex; accept eventual consistency |\n544: | Sandbox IP changes | Medium | Low | Refresh SandboxInfo on connection failure; implement retry with fresh lookup |\n545: \n546: ## Future Considerations\n547: \n548: 1. **Circuit Breaker Pattern** - Implement circuit breaker for WorkloadManager calls\n549: 2. **Metrics and Observability** - Add Prometheus metrics (request latency, error rates, concurrency usage)\n550: 3. **Distributed Tracing** - Integrate OpenTelemetry for request tracing across components\n551: 4. **Rate Limiting** - Per-client or per-session rate limiting beyond global concurrency\n552: 5. **Request/Response Logging** - Structured logging for audit and debugging\n553: 6. **WebSocket Support** - Upgrade HTTP connections to WebSocket for streaming use cases\n554: 7. **Session Affinity** - Sticky sessions for multi-replica router deployments\n555: 8. **Hot Reload** - Dynamic configuration reload without restart\n556: 9. **Multi-Cluster Routing** - Route to sandboxes across multiple Kubernetes clusters\n557: 10. **Canary Deployments** - Traffic splitting for sandbox version upgrades\n558: \n559: ## References\n560: \n561: - [net/http/httputil.ReverseProxy](https://pkg.go.dev/net/http/httputil#ReverseProxy)\n562: - [Gin Web Framework](https://gin-gonic.com/)\n563: - [golang-jwt/jwt](https://github.com/golang-jwt/jwt)\n564: - [HTTP/2 and h2c](https://httpwg.org/specs/rfc7540.html)\n565: - Session Routing Spec: `session-routing/spec.md`\n566: - Deployment Spec: `deployment/spec.md`\n567: - Client-go Documentation: `deployment/client-go.md`\n568: - Related: `changes/AR-004/` (WorkloadManager HTTP Service)\n569: - Related: `changes/AR-008/` (Session Store)\n\n(End of file - total 569 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-009: Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n\n## Purpose\n\nThis proposal defines the HTTP reverse proxy core implementation for the `pkg/router` module in the AgentCube project. The router is responsible for:\n\n1. **Session-aware traffic routing** - Resolve or create sessions via workload manager, route HTTP requests to appropriate sandbox endpoints\n2. **Reverse proxy functionality** - Proxy HTTP traffic to sandbox pods with proper URL rewriting and header forwarding\n3. **JWT authentication** - Sign outbound requests to sandboxes with JWT tokens for authentication\n4. **Connection management** - Handle connection pooling, health checks, and concurrency limiting\n5. **Activity tracking** - Update session last-activity timestamps in the store for idle cleanup\n\nThe router serves as the primary entry point for all HTTP invocations targeting agent runtimes and code interpreters.\n\n## Scope\n\n**Module:** `pkg/router`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-qwen3.5-plus_20260410T163217Z/changes/AR-009/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775849144538,"end":1775849144557}}}}
